This place is worth a try. They have large portions for convenient prices. Constantly well kept and with fantastic ambience. Will come back again.

I came here just for the happy hour, but I would like to return for lunch. Bewarned that it does get loud at dinner since they have a live band playing, and they request a $10 addition for each table for the band- very reasonable. They have a back patio too and I would maybe check that out for dinner since it might be a little more quiet there.  The happy hour is wonderful! I came during daiquiri week and they had $6 daiquiris and margaritas going. Both were really refreshing and well prepared and mixed. I would say the marg is a little sweeter than I would like but thats an easy solve with the bartender.  Dinner is more tapas style - you don't actually get tapas but they have smaller plates. I loved the charcuterie board.  The space is a narrow one and they have little patio tables for 2 people, with a couple of larger tables in the window that are for about 5-6 people. The window seating is the nicest, reminds me of little cafes in England and smaller towns. It definitely gets busy at night with the number of people who come there.  it can also get really loud from Friday to Sunday due to the live band.

Would highly recommend- and will definitely be coming back

One of my favorite jazz places in NYC. I haven't been to a concert there that I didn't like. I haven't had a drink I didn't want to order another glass of. I haven't had the interactions with staff I didn't enjoy. I didn't eat there myself (past 9 pm is too late for dinner for me), but I have heard that their food is delicious as well. The audience is always a mixed crowd of all ages from very young to very old (love!). The vibe is awesome. And I really appreciate their respect for the musicians. Most of the time the customers are respectful and quiet during the performance but once in a while there is a couple of bad apples that tend to treat live music as a background for their conversations. The staff puts musicians first, and will always put a stop to that, which is really great. Not a single visit to NY goes by for me without catching at least one show at LunÀtico.

Additionally, the staff is wonderful (Naaj), the drinks are well developed, and the music (live) is supreme. If you're in bed-Stuy and you are looking for the best kind of live music you ought to pass through Bar LunÀtico... and stay for a while, you'll be glad you did.
